3 Days to Race - Flow intervals (8x1min)

The last days of preparation include some flow intervals to get the legs ready for speed and keep the feet light! 

I always try to put in some drills before intervals to improve runningform, wake up all muscle fibers and activate full ROM(range of motion)

#running #run #runningeconomy #runner #runnerlife #race #ready #lining @lining.official @lining.sportbiz.dk #sport #halfmarathon #worldchampionship #military #runningtechnique #drills

Read along for Info about the last preparation period before Half marathon Luzern: 

1. After nationals in Sep. I had 3 weeks loading all the km and intervals possible for a Vet. Student. It included 100-110km a week w. 3-4 quality workouts. Besides running I tried get a bit of cycling and swimming for active recovery. Because of the time issue, I didn’t priorities strength/core training, (unfortunately). The 3week block ended with a weekend training camp with @forsvarets_landshold_lob 🔥

2. Step down period lasted 2 weeks; The easy weeks started of with autumn break from Uni. So, I had plenty of time to recover between runs, and I had time to catch up on school. At the same time I got to spend some time with family and friends on a weekend trip ♥️

3. Plan for the last 2weeks:
- Cut down on the high amount of KM. Short easy runs (40-50min) – Slow pace!
- First week, still doing 3 quality workouts, but gradually shorter. Tuesday: 2x10min at HM pace. Thursday: 25min @3.40.  Sunday: 8x1,5min Buildup to 3.10.
- The second week: Even shorter easy runs (25-45min) and only quality with a focus on technic, light feet and getting a good flow in the run. Tuesday: 4x3min @3.20. Thursday: 8x1min flow.
Take off Friday to Luzern. – easy run Friday and Sunday - Raceday Sunday (All Out)😉

My take on energy, during and after workouts:

It is very important to get enough energy during training, and especielly the longer runs and interval sessions. This improves the performance and revovery. However, there is a differens in how and when I take the energy.

During intevals I fuel up with geels during warmup and  with energy-mixed water in between intervals if possible and needed. Here I aim for 60-100 g/hour

During longruns on the treadmill it is easier to fuel up through water-mix while going, but on the longer outdoor runs, I priorities to be fully hydrated beforehand. Then i only need to fuel up with geels and energy-snacks on the go, which is easier to carry than a waterbottle. On long runs above 1,5 hour I aim for +80 g/hour

Post workout I also aim to refill my glycogen reserves (mix in the reel). Especially if I don’t take in energy during a workout. Otherwise a protein and fiber rich meal will do the job for me🤩

Have fun🏃🏽
